Parliament did not support the amendment liberating Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal a paragraph of the Criminal Code amendment condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
At the second reading, MEPs rejected the amendment that would pave the way for the release of the jailed ex-prisoner.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for entering into an allegedly unfavourable contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final, the appeal of the convicted is to be discussed by the court in December.
Tymoshenko refers to the verdict as a political vendetta of the regime, suspicion of court bias has triggered the trial in the West as well.
The proposal to remove section 365 from the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the ex-minister was convicted, was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
It took 226 votes to pass.
