Obese child's dining room: breakfast and dinner snacks
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of schoolchildren being overweight and 5 percent of children being obese.
Obese children, on the other hand, mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to a recent survey.
Again, it shows how important it is for the healthy development of the human environment in which it grows and the patterns that surround it.
On the tables of obese children, for example, sausages appear up to half more often than in families of children with normal weight.
Fried fries had to dinner the day before the research associated with an educational event called Obesity is no coincidence more than 19 percent obese.
In fat families, too, it is not a habit to exercise, which is true for most families of today’s schoolchildren – only 15 percent of children said that their parents would find time to exercise at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place at the end of last year’s school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
It was already the second year of the Obesity event not a coincidence, which is supported by the General Health Insurance and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 students from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Proper nutrition and enough exercise in the family is one of the determining factors, which causes a dramatically increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
"For example, only half of those surveyed said they ate breakfast-meal-meal-meal-dinner five times a day, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," the study found.
Without breakfast and evening snack
Experts point out that relative details are also essential for healthy development, including, for example, the regular time of family breakfasts.
In the Czech Republic, at the same time, only 23 percent of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast.
In most families, everyone eats alone.
And the worst was the finding that in a tenth of households there is no breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The survey showed that families of obese children are much more likely to consume unhealthy fries.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonade (70 percent) every day.
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed regularly participate in sports, their parents had less than half the result - 15 percent.
Build your own dining room
The next part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to build their own dining room according to their own taste and opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
Among their favorite foods is a lot of floury, massive and sweet dishes.
"Apprehensive is especially the great popularity of sweet lemonades," said the final report to the survey.
For lunch, the main meal was the pasta, just above the poultry.
But the children practically did not want legumes at all and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetable dishes is low.
An Appeal to Health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the Obesity Awareness Lecture, it is no coincidence that in many cases there has been a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition," the project's results state.
This was particularly striking for sweet lemonades, for example, where more children would begin to prefer plain water.
Children were also much more likely to check poultry and fish as the main meal of the day in the questionnaire, and would limit sweets and dumplings.
