In Need for Speed: The Run, the race takes place all over America.
Testimonials
Originally a carefree ride turns into a routine morning commute to the sled because of a series of completely unnecessary errands.
Ambition has succeeded to a large extent, but it is not valid when no one has obviously wanted to do anything extra.
The new track, subtitled The Run, was highly anticipated before its release.
He promised that the flying Need for Speed racing series would once again take a bit of a new direction, and from the playable shows it seemed like a game that would not have to be just in numbers in the action racing genre.
We were also curious how the embedded passages will turn out, in which the main character will get out of the car and run after his own.
As with the NFS series, a lot of the results are a little different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole thing pulls down a few unnecessary bugs that have been appearing in the series for more or less a few years.
So it's not actually a mistake, but rather a manifestation of some kind of incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal nature and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You will be driving on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to be the first to arrive in New York.
The idea carries several interesting elements with it.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race goes on a different track and the given stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It doesn’t feel like the game is still offering the same thing.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing worldly.
But driving through the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are from time to time strewn with some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get stuck in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught by the avalanche.
In addition, individual races are quite well placed behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the required number of opponents (essentially a classic race), then you catch up with time (a classic match with stops) and then a duel with a single opponent awaits you.
From time to time, the police will also be involved in this, which makes all your efforts even more unpleasant.
What's new is the passages outside the car.
Rather, it’s just an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right times.
Nothing complicated.
But it will surprise you that these passages are in the game much less than you would expect (specifically maybe even just three).
As a result, however, it is in the favor of the thing, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of the above, it thus ranks among the elements that enhance the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is definitely no longer something, but it cannot be said that it would be a negation.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-oriented racing, the driving model here still fits quite well, although we could find a better one with the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
However, the problems begin to appear after some time.
Unlike the car, the car is no longer in good condition.
From a game of this type we do not expect to count complex deformations and collisions, but if practically before any impact to any object you have no idea how your car will behave, then perhaps everything is not quite right.
Typically, when passing cars in close proximity or passing cars in normal operation, sometimes you will only lick each other slightly, but at other times in almost identical situations your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
Or even a direct attack.
Thanks to the system of restarts it does not matter in any particular way, but it will degrade you reliably.
Restarts are handled in such a way that if you break up or go far off the track, the game throws you back to the last catch point on the track.
However, only five restarts are available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it's more of a help in case something doesn't work out than you can rely on them.
But sometimes even restarts will not help, only the need to learn a certain stage of the race will solve them.
A big disadvantage of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some curves need to pass in a specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civilian" cars in the same configuration at a given place, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially true in situations where you see an opponent passing easily in front of you between two cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "counted" so that the situation always occurs right in front of your nose.
Opponents have another advantage.
Throughout the game you will come across several places where, again regardless of the time, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
The most striking thing at the end of the game is the long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously get in front of you at any cost.
When it goes in front of you, it makes the visibility of the cars in front of you worse, so at first you can get a good massage.
You can understand the intention to make the game more tense and adrenaline-fueled, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably quickly disgust you.
And it’s a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and places are so action-packed that sometimes you literally can’t keep track of where it’s flying.
And it doesn’t really matter if it’s a concept with fifty unique tracks, sorting races so boredom doesn’t stand a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas pumps at the roads, because it is there that you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you are enough with what you just have.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American bullfighters on straight highways and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example after winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common for challenges and story.
To get a higher level of the driver, various items are unlocked: starting with the car and ending with the background for the profile.
At the same time, it is again connected to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares your achieved results with other players and provides other community functions.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you will get to the tunnel of the metro (below), where you can take it in the dark on the tracks (below).
On the tachometer you can see the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (below) and in the rear a set of meters will be placed and you will be uncompromisingly shot down.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a discussion for a few more days about whether no one really thought a bit when creating the game, or whether the authors think we are really such a big fool.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It freezes so that in some more tense moments, the shooting decreases, and in some cases it is quite tragic.
But this is especially true of storms with a larger number of participants, when smooth shooting would no longer be valid for you anyway.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an attempt to appeal to the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category "every dog different village" was created, but it can be assumed that due to listening to music, probably someone will not buy the game.
The overall feel of Need for Speed: The Run is so very sad.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of the NFS in recent years.
This is how the game looks unfinished.
The fun is sure to be fine, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will shake your eyes with the power of airport spotlights.
