If someone were to search for the word that would most accurately express IBM’s strategy, the closest one would probably be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is perceived as a very contemporary company, and yet it has been a hundred years since its foundation.
The basis of this longevity was laid by the first head of the company, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already broken the password that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the basis of Watson’s carefully built corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking is a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values and was not afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the second hundred," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO.
A well-developed system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the care of his employees in a similar way to the businessman Bata in the Czech Republic - the people from IBM were among the first American employees to have paid leave, insurance from the employer plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system to reward the best inventors and businessmen.
IBM has a long-term relationship with the customer.
From the beginning, the company was brilliant at extracting talent - as one of the world's first companies, it abolished any discrimination, so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisana to be replaced by a woman, Virginia Rometty, at the head of IBM next year.
She has been working at IBM for 30 years and is still the head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been making so-called pits, online brainstorming, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder there are so many ideas - almost half a million people work in the company.
An institution with a good name
A firm position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, IBM had a concept of an institution rather than just a technology company," said Harvard Business School professor and author of the book about IBM Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems through the use of technology,” added George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the market and creating the market directly.
IBM - or "Big Blue", as it is known in the United States because of its logo - has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a hundred years.
It is arguably the most versatile technology company - developing hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any U.S. technology company, and five of its employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Her inventions include an ATM, a payment card, a financial swap, a barcode or a floppy disk.
IBM, with about $220 billion, became the second-largest technology company by market capitalization this year (the first being Apple), when it surpassed Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
A look ahead
Not all products and innovations have caught the eye of customers and times - for example, IBM failed to bet on its own OS/2 operating system, online services Prodigy or IBM PCjr computers.
“If your business is built on moving forward, you can’t emotionally tie yourself to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on many platforms – and if they don’t work, abandon them.
Unlike, for example, rival Microsoft, which basically stands and falls on the Windows operating system.
Prospective technology
IBM’s sales are largely driven by services, with software and hardware accounting for about a fifth of them.
As early as 1990, with more than half the share, he was the most powerful hardware representative.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion worth of low-yield assets, and has invested $58 billion in the acquisition of promising technologies.
Investments have continued since 2008, the first time the world was overrun by the modern financial crisis.
IBM is acting on the advice of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM is going through the current crisis untouched.
Since the beginning of 2008, IBM’s share price has risen by 120 percent, and the company’s net profit has been steadily increasing.
IBM’s motto is to change everything, but not its values.
Therefore, it can be expected that even if there is another crisis, this flexible giant will manage it.
History of IBM: From cheese slicer to space flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, originally called the Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The IBM name wasn’t adopted until 1924 – it was originally a brand used for the company’s branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for later IBM was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They owned technologies such as the famous "pissers," i.e. hours recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired the company's supervisory board.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of a rival firm, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on an invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for business – from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson’s management, the company doubled its turnover to $9 million and began expanding to all parts of the world.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior, after almost forty years in the executive chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA fly to space — to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous man-to-the-moon flight.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "poodle" that set the computer standard of the time, called the IBM 5150, came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold Lenovo’s computer manufacturing business to China, bought the consulting arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, and began to devote itself fully to high-value-added consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make smart use of technologies in previously unplanned areas and to improve the situation, for example, in transport or city administration.
For the business sector, IBM recently introduced the platform “Smarter Commerce”, which helps traders to manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM has a strong history in the country.
She founded her branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM Czech Republic, there is also a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
