How Tour Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time were overwhelmingly selling only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus traveled on holiday to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Society of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand up to the front overnight with a sleeping bag or have a "well-known" in the travel office.
But it was not won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) on the way to the West.
By far the most frequent, however, the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, which resulted in a large number of chats and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this habit survives to this day.
The Czech Republic has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was our highest holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia until 1989, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the turn of the 1990s, the visa requirement in neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which triggered a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czechs slept in parks in tents, because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs’ travel during this time was to drive their own food, cans, salamis, etc., to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally freely buy the Western currency after many destinations for years.
However, our standard of living and, with it, average wages were rising, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare trips by charter airlines since 1997, which has resulted in an incredible discount on air travel due to the possibility to book bulk discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already had visa-free access to virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the US, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000 when, thanks to considerable demand, it was sent from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to the exotic, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters have been flying with Czech tourists every year to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. visa for Czech tourists was revoked, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history and spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person for one foreign holiday, including the cost of living.
