In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to admit new billion-dollar losses, the president of the board of directors Marcel Ospel, in 2006 still the second highest-paid board of directors in Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008, a disaster ensued: UBS stood by its misinvestment during the financial crisis before the collapse and had to be rescued by the state.
The Nationalbank bought from UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs in mandatory convertible bonds, for which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland has been shaken - for it has noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it has such large banks in its territory.
