Peter Englund’s emotionally powerful new book, Beauty and the Sorrow: The Confidential History of World War I (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War), begins with a long list of characters coming out of it.
One tip on how to behave at the moment: Carefully tear out this page and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know all the people in Mr. Englund's novel, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a beacon - at a time when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite accurately, as an "anti-historical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It is not even a book about what happened, explains the author, but rather "a book about what it was like". It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sorrow" combines the war experience of 20 fewer dozen men and women on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, rescue drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad, or die.
Their lives flicker like flames of candles lit in the church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fate, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from the classic historical novels.
He edits the idea that the First World War was all about the terrible trench battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with the bee's nest falling on them, having to spend Christmas in the shade of the pyramids or struggling with the presence of tse-tse flies.
From the very beginning, it was a very touching read.
War devours people's lives like some natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling like gunpowder.
When gunfire starts ringing in the distance and you're the woman who's home with your kids, will you run away or stay?
Who's really getting close?
Almost no one understands what’s going on, not even why the whole war was started.
"A vacuum created by a lack of facts," observed Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, suppositions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are taken from biographies, letters, and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and enticing, but thanks to the inclusion of small moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them deal with suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Replacements, everywhere substitutes."
"Café apron, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It refers to "meat made from pressed rice cooked in rind fat (and supplemented with a fake wooden bone), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles".
He mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
An American finds an inner urge to savagery and brutality, and then declares war: "In the end, you will understand that this is human nature, not sitting in comfortable armchairs with a cigarette and a whisky, in the evening newspapers or in a good book, pretending to be a Jew, and pretending to be a Jew.
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he is most likely going to die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
"When a person finally comes to terms with sacrificing himself, he would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience," he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “convict who is secretly hanged.”
Other remarks concern the departure of the old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
"Conflict has increasingly become an economic competition and a competitive struggle," writes Mr. Englund, "a war between factories."
He captured what he calls “a new kind of beast of the coming century: a eloquent and ideologically sworn mass murderer in tailor-made clothes who carries out his bloodshed without getting up from the table.”
People behave completely unexpectedly, insidiousness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch some kind of sexual illness from prostitutes in order to avoid serving on the front lines.
“The most glaring example of this behavior was the gonococcal pus trade that soldiers bought and rubbed their genitals with in the hope that it would end up in a hospital,” he wrote.
"The most desperate of them had him in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives."
In this translation from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is shrewd, but it does not prove anything, which is perfectly suited to his human subject.
In dozens of small outputs, he captures the way the war “dissolved absolutely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.”
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are forced to fight.
The best books about the First World War mostly worked with hints, such as "World War I and Modern Memories" by Paul Fussell or novels like "On the Western Front of Peace" by Erich Maria Remarque.
Mr. Englund prefers an unconventional concept.
His book has the most shattering endings, which are unprecedented in popular scholarly literature.
But I will not reveal it to you.
However, you will feel as if the author suddenly jumped out of the book, ripped the page from your list of heroes out of your hand and set it on fire.
