The union of auxiliary workers will sue the city for dismissal
The unions representing the hundreds of school helpers who lost their jobs last month are planning to sue the city on Wednesday. They claim that the dismissal was not necessary and, moreover, it was about discrimination, due to the disproportionate impact on schools attended by poor students.
The judicial review is probably the last option that the District Council 37 trade unions have left in their efforts to reverse the dismissal decision.
On October 7, six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parents’ coordinators and other employees, who were among the city’s worst paid employees, lost their jobs. Their dismissals were described by the union leaders as retribution for the city’s failure last spring to grant him access to health care.
City officials have categorically denied the allegation.
At a city council meeting last month, education minister Dennis M. Walcott said the release was part of a budget approved in June.
One of the members of the council immediately disputed the fact that the budget did not mention the release of aid workers in any specific way.
District Council 37 officials announced that they had already filled in the necessary documents and warned the Department of Education that they would sue him. On Wednesday, they will convene a press conference where they will formally announce the lawsuit at the Manhattan Supreme Court.
The defendants in the lawsuit will be Mr. Walcott and the Department of Education, while the plaintiff side will be eight dismissed workers, all of whom are African-American or Hispanic, as well as most of the other assistants who lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, a spokeswoman for the city's legal department, said the city had not yet seen the lawsuit and would not comment on individual charges.
According to a complaint filed by the New York Times, the unions focused on the number of people released in poor parts of the city to support their claims of unfair treatment, because they believe that poor schools have lost more assistants because they have been denied funding for a long time.
They point out that while schools in the Staten Island area did not drop out at all and in the Upper East Side area at least, in Brooklyn, in the District 23 area in Brownsville, 17 school assistants were lost, and in the District 8 and 9 areas in the South Bronx, 46 assistants were even released.
He recalls that at Public School 36 in Harlem, five out of eight assistants lost their jobs, despite the fact that it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty. The lawsuit says: "It is not a neighborhood full of mobile parents who can afford to make up for the budget deficit."
Public School 36’s budget was cut by 3.26% this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way bonus funds are calculated for every enrolled poor student.
The unions, among other things, claim that the principals of secondary schools could have been confused in the way in which a document approving the dismissal of the parental coordinators was written.
The document used the word "excess" to describe the event, i.e. to cancel the position, although this word is much more often used to describe the transfer of the teacher from the school payroll to the database of available workers whose salary is paid by the central authority.
"Sixty-six parental coordinators have been released," the complaint states, "and not just moved to the available staff position in the database."
The mission is over, Congress is ready to accept an agreement on the situation in Libya
Finally, it seems that the Republicans and Democrats in Congress agree on something regarding the uprising in Libya.
But before that happened, the revolution had to succeed, the long-ruling dictator Muammar Gaddafi had to be captured and killed, and the participation of the United States forces ended.
On Tuesday, the Senate's International Relations Commission will decide on a statement supported by President John Kerry (Mass.) along with Senators John McCain (Ariz.) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Conn.), in which it should congratulate the Libyans on their successful uprising and "for American unity".
“With this statement, we want to appreciate the courage of the people of Libya who started rebuilding their country,” Kerry said.
"Both sides of the political spectrum would like to express their support for their democratic efforts."
The above-mentioned sentences may seem innocent, but no debate on Libya has been easy until now.
Over the years, lawmakers from both sides have been arguing with each other and the White House over the wording of a series of statements to approve or reject the United States’ military role in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain introduced a resolution authorizing the limited use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The proposal was rejected in the House because of differences of opinion between the two political parties, so it was never voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that the motion was rejected in the House, the House also rejected measures that would stop funding U.S. operations in Libya.
By doing so, the U.S. mission in Libya found itself literally in the legislative clearinghouse — Congress has criticized the way President Obama runs the mission, but apparently its members haven’t bothered it enough to stop supporting him in his actions.
The Congressional heaviness was eventually preceded by other events.
The rebels captured Tripoli in August and Gaddafi was killed on October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31st.
The Senate may now be ready to act.
In its statement, the International Relations Commission "congratulates the people of Libya for their immense courage and admirable tenacity in their efforts to liberate their people" and "praises the men and women of the armed forces of the United States and their allies who have engaged in an operation to protect the Libyan people."
The statement also "confirms the national interest of the United States in the successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya."
Will the new proposal receive full support from the Commission on International Relations, or will the legislators be split again in two, as was the case when the June proposal was approved?
The last version was opposed by Senator Richard G. Lugar (Ind.), the chief representative of the Republican Party in the commission.
Lugar's spokesman said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new proposal.
The House will vote this week on an amendment to the Constitution that would require a balanced budget, which should be the top legislative priority of almost all Republicans and Democrats in Congress.
This measure, advocated by Bob Goodlatt (Va.), will be the first addition to the Constitution concerning a budget or other subject on which the entire House or Senate will vote.
For the time being, the other legislators, despite considerable efforts, have not yet succeeded in pushing their proposals to the very vote.
Goodlatt's proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the constitution that were introduced in Congress and touched on a wide range of different topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal submitted to the House and the Senate - and others are just small exchanges of others.
Only in the House can you find at least 15 versions of the balanced budget addendum and another handful that would like to "regulate federal spending".
Some of the proposals are identical, but their proponents — especially beginning Republicans who want to improve their reputations — can boast of their “authorship.”
The revenue on the regulation of the budget, which was approved in August, required the House and the Senate to vote on the addition to the balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding declaration in support of the creation of such an addendum.
In addition to the budget, several members want to discuss restrictions on the number of periods in which members of Congress could serve, while José E. Serrano (N.Y.) wants to increase the number of periods that may be in office as president.
Representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) offered a number of supplements that would guarantee, among other things, the right to quality education and medical care.
The permanent proposal remains an addendum prohibiting same-sex marriage and an addendum prohibiting the burning of the state flag.
Some lawmakers also want to allow the repeal of federal laws in the event that two-thirds of states oppose them.
Although members of Congress seem to be very active in designing various add-ons, they are not significantly out of the ordinary compared to previous years.
In the 111th Congress they offered 77 additions, while in the 100th Congress there were 66.
Their activity even pales in comparison to the early 1990s, when, according to the statistics of the Senate Library, members offered more than 150 additions every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than current politicians.
The last amendment that was added - the 27th amendment - was ratified in 1992, but in fact it was proposed by Congress in 1789.
