So completely opposite impressions only illustrate the difficult relationship between the army and the often measured, sometimes celebratory, American public.
The army is boundless with praise for its victims.
But this praise is worth something, say the soldiers.
The public is behaving more and more as if they were pitying an individual in uniform.
"We are not victims at all," said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded troops in Iraq and will soon leave Afghanistan.
"But it seems the only way some can support us is to put us in the role of unhappy souls."
This topic is very sensitive to army commanders who do not want to look ungrateful or spoil their relationships with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger that the troops returning from Vietnam had to face was much worse.
As a result, most of the words of regret are spoken in silence and in privacy among war veterans.
When the two sons of retired Colonel Mark Cancian returned from combat operations, where they served as members of the Marine Corps, their father warned them that people outside the army would look at their service from two angles.
From the point of view of some, he will feel respect and wonder, because they defeated the enemy insurgents and visited exotic places.
But others will be puzzled if “a bad, violent veteran is not hiding under the surface,” said Cancian, who took part in the fighting in Iraq and took his place in Washington’s government upon his return.
He claimed that when he was looking for a job, some of the people who interviewed him inconspicuously suggested that he could resist the stress associated with working in Washington so soon after returning from a fight.
“When you talk about your service, you have to count on negative reactions,” Cancian taught his sons.
The concern of the military stems in part from American indifference to war.
Successes on the battlefield rarely garner recognition in a country that has little awareness of its own army and finds little of its own benefit in the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
"As a nation, we no longer value military heroism as it was common during World War II," said Lt. Gen. David Barno, who commanded U.S. troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, the recognition by politicians and the public is focused mainly on the suffering of men in arms.
Soldiers are awarded for the number of actions they have suffered, the number of friends they have lost, or the extent of their injuries.
The military is facing increasing pressure to take tough action against rape.
This week, it will be decided whether to open a trial of 28 women and men against the army for alleged inaction in the event of rape.
