The indictment was filed in February by Washington lawyer Susan Burke, and the plaintiff had 17 members at the time. However, over the following months, the number of defendants increased to 28-25 women and three men, all of whom claim to have been raped or otherwise sexually assaulted by their co-workers in the past.
Burke says he's going after the highest-ranking army commanders because the problem starts with them.
