Burke also says she has contacted at least 400 other survivors since February, many of whom could become part of other lawsuits filed in the future.
Her strategy: Rather than pooling all the charges into this case — stacking all the eggs in one basket, as she says — she will file lawsuits in multiple different cases if pressure doesn’t need to be eased.
The defense team is led by U.S. Attorney Neil MacBride, who along with his colleagues has filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents obtained by Newsweek detail the defense’s strategy – essentially that current or former soldiers cannot sue the military for injuries they suffered as members of the armed forces.
Under a 1950 Supreme Court order called the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries suffered by soldiers in active service.
"The alleged injuries relate to the military service of the plaintiffs," the document reads.
