Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Are Examining You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man presenting his anti-immigrant views on the internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to a July murderous rampage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was definitely not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social media sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t that hard at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The amount of personal information on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that it was enough for scientists to simply take advantage of the ad on the site and, as a result, pinpoint the demographic group they were looking for – something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, and they focused their attention on them and sent out advertisements to them. But instead of inviting them to join a newly formed group or offering them some diet products, they encouraged them to fill them out.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans from 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without even having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are all young men, spurred by the growing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends hiding with status updates, wall posts, and the push of the “Like” button.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them, on average, provides three different data per day, which makes this social network literally "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic works, in the name of which there is a word Facebook, has increased to an estimated 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the ability to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to conduct a survey among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side where they'd never let you go," Bartlett says.
"All of this is knocking down Facebook - you just go straight to them."
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify a social-health problem and avoid it.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken outbursts on Facebook were far more at risk for alcoholism than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moren suggests that students’ peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunk statuses.
"The problem can't be solved if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, a co-author of Dr. Moren and director of the Center for Children's Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children that we would not otherwise have had a chance to discover."
Facebook itself is constantly probing its users’ data.
The site’s information team has compiled statistics on the relationship between relationship statuses and Valentine’s Day, election turnout in 2010 and the nation’s satisfaction ratio (mainly using information they had access to – internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should have its own information treasure to back up and down).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site needs to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules about how to collect data offline. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most users even thought that scientists could look into their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"When it came to them, they took it so that the information was only between them and their friends."
It is also important to consider the question of methodology.
Even when researching offline, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to verify how much of the information on the profile and the posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent years researching new technologies, thinks that pencil and notebook are still the best possible tool that can be used in research.
“When you go into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” he says.
“Social research should be about society and social activities – and a hell of a lot of social activities are still going on offline.”
