7 Lessons from a Lost Interview with Steve Jobs in a Movie Heading to the Movies This Week
When Steve Jobs died on October 5, the opinions of people who compared him to Henry Ford began to appear – and elected him for his genius as the Greatest Modern Inventor.
In a recently re-released interview with Jobs, which was dusted for a special movie heading into theaters this week, it will be a fact for all Apple fans that his creative mind perfectly understands the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer and a self-proclaimed member of the hippie movement, but also a pedantic organizer and a man who fits every detail into the smallest detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffer "assuming that a really great idea is 90 percent of their work... [but] it's an excellent one.
In 1995, Bob Cringley worked on the TV show Triumph of Computer Madness, which discussed the dawn of personal computers. During filming, a unique, more than hour-long interview took place.
It had been ten years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he had been working full-time with his new computer company NeXT, and impatiently watching the general public embrace the internet.
In the end, only a short part of the entire Cringley interview was used in the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were said to have been lost in transit.
Shortly after Jobs's death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
It is this material, slightly cut, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: A Lost Interview, which is heading to select cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
To someone who has become famous for his reluctance to provide longer interviews, Jobs seems surprisingly excited to be able to talk about his technological philosophy and business strategies.
He also appears to be a very thoughtful man.
Four times during the interview, there will be a longer pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when it is seen how Jobs perfectly thinks the answer to be as accurate and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, when he is impatient with Cringley’s questions and drives him to get to more important issues and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of the Pixar, iPod or iPhone, and horribly prophetic ideas pop up in it when Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right and wrong while offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It’s one thing to read the post-mortem reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about Jobs, whom we see here as a keen dreamer in the bloom of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things can and should look like.
It did not take long, and after he had uttered his thoughts, he began to put them into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from the Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
“During the years of business, I’ve always asked myself, ‘Why are you doing this?’ and the answer was always the same: ‘Well, that’s just how it’s done.’
No one knows why they do what they do, they never think deeply about things related to business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs goes on to describe his effort to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way costs were recorded - often beginning with the inscription "standard costs", about their amount he could only imagine. At that moment he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine business costs within a moment.
How he made the rosary for the Pope:
Jobs recalls the “Blue Box” he designed with Steve Wozniak — a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
A number have been written about the device in the past, but Jobs’ enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as a tool of power is literally contagious.
It tells how Wozniak tested the devices using a paid phone and allowed them to connect from one AT&T network to another during the call, while using as many satellites as possible.
"At least half a dozen times we've been around the world like this, so when we shouted something into the pay phone, it came a minute later from the second phone at the door," Jobs laughs.
“We were young, and we found that we could build a thing that is capable of running billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us made a tiny thing that could control a much larger plant - it was an incredible experience and I think Apple would never have been born without it.
Jobs goes on to describe the joke they almost ended with Wozniak. Through the Blue Box in the middle of the night, they called the Vatican and asked if they could talk to the Pope, making the best of Henry Kissinger.
Gradually, members of the Catholic Church were called up to speak to an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and it was not until just before they had awakened the Pope himself on the phone that the couple squirmed and put down their headphones.
How he fell in love with technology (and phoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and was looking for spare parts to build his pacemaker, he found Bill Hewlett's number on his phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute interview, Jobs had already secured a summer brigade at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company really is and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research lab in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was as big as a suitcase, had a CRT monitor, and I instantly fell in love with it.
As a teenager, I progressed higher and higher in HP, hung around the computer and started writing programs for it.
How Innovation Invents:
In several places during the interview, Jobs talks about how he invents new products while running.
In the beginning of his career, when he went to sell a couple of PCBs, one customer asked him to put together a whole computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days to invent, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
When he was later at Apple, he recalled the problems they faced when developing a computer mouse:
“I remember fighting pretty wildly... screaming at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] to stop having fun, I went out and found a designer.”
Ninety days later, we were able to produce a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies breathe:
Long before he led Apple’s resurrection, Jobs prudently predicted that many industry leaders would backtrack on his vision and lose their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
At this point, sales and marketing are already in place, so companies are run by people who are in charge of this, while people who are in charge of their own products are kept out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that has led the company to its unshakable position is now replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products – skill and technical knowledge are necessary.
This is exactly what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned virtually the entire computer industry.
It could be ten times bigger than it is, it could be a Microsoft of the 1990s...
Instead of winning, they won by losing.
Taking Innovation as a Form of Art:
"Between a great idea and a great product there is still a long way to go and a lot of work to do... and as that great idea develops, it changes and grows."
You will learn a lot about him during that time.
You have to come up with a number of compromises - certain things just electrons, glass, robots or factories do not force you to do.
You have to keep in mind 5,000 things all the time - different concepts - and put them together...
After all, it’s about taste – you try to think about the best things that humanity has ever created, and in some ways you try to project them into what you’re doing yourself.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I was never ashamed to steal the best ideas.
Macintosh was so amazing and successful because the people who worked at it were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians and, by the way, the best computer experts in the world.
Without computers and new technologies, they would be able to do amazing things in completely different industries.
