We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called "initial observation".
This will give him a better understanding of what to compare it with.
Notice the holding of the subject's body, his laughter, working with his voice.
You should know if someone is habitually knocking on their feet so that you don’t wrongly accuse them of lying just because they start knocking on their feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to determine the clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But take it only as warning signs, not as proof of a lie.
People who tell lies can stop moving the upper half of their body when they try to remember their fictional story, they can turn the tips of the shoes to the door, lean to the east, significantly change the posture of the body or reveal the "crazy after the conversation" - the excess of the relief of change is a half-step away.
