A new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that is holding this country above the abyss of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet tomorrow with the Italian president to introduce him to a new government that will face a crisis that is holding this country above the abyss of an economic catastrophe and that has put the entire eurozone in danger.
The presidential palace issued a report in which it announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to represent a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, that is, in a much shorter time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to fight against the political and financial crisis, due to which the amount of debt has climbed to an unsustainable level.
A new administration led by former European Commissioner Montim must approve a tough package of austerity measures required by European leaders, only to restore Italy's shattered credibility.
Due to the volatility of the markets, interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity limit of 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailout, are under pressure to accelerate.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian employers’ organisation Confindustria, told reporters after a meeting with Monti: “We said we would be very supportive of this government.”
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this burning situation.
Monti’s hopes of success were greatly increased thanks to the support of PDL’s Silvia Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined for good results," Angelina Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant, as up to now a number of its members have stood against the government with the technocratic majority that Monti is putting together.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong support from parliament in order to push for unpopular austerity reforms.
Any impediment or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has added to the pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could spell disaster.
Monti began talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women’s organisations.
The round of talks will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, which allowed for very rapid action in response to the crisis.
After a short fall at the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond yields returned to a critical level, reacting to uncertainty over whether the new prime minister would reap success.
To save Italy, whose public debt is <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.8 trillion, would be beyond the scope of the eurozone’s current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should stay in power until the next elections, which are scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will give him time only to carry out reforms, and then announce early elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that this government must consist only of experts to bring Italy out of the hardships the country has gotten into due to financial pressure.
Political sources said that mutual mistrust and disagreement between the parties complicate the attempt to include both political figures in the government.
