The quintet included the country in its tour on the occasion of the celebration of twenty years of existence
"The road to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality"
In an exclusive interview for Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that for them the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
So said bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is on tour in South America on the occasion of the celebration of twenty years of existence and on Sunday the 20th will be on a unique stop in Central America.
This day will perform at 19:30 at the National Stadium together with the angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is a sample interview, the full transcript of which can be found on La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n's website.
For your Costa Rican fans, it is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The journey to Costa Rica is also our dream, which becomes a reality.
In South and Central America we are barely the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It is a beautiful country and I believe that we will be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to be able to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally adore the band here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your biggest fans?
Thank you for staying with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have been over the course of a few weeks.
We performed some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope to get in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. So we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no restrictions that we couldn't do.
We will try to present the best possible show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and varied repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why? !
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes other songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs we’ll play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played for a long time, we focus on them and we are also surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
This tour celebrates 20 years of artistic trajectory.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yeah, that's for sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we'd be in one big rock band and that we'd be staying in it for more than 20 years, and that sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we have been given and we are impressed that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We’re lucky to be able to see the places we’ve always wanted.
We couldn't have gotten any better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the emergence of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, where the giants themselves are represented.
The people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It’s surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, too often it doesn’t happen.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to arise from one city at a time.
We are proud of that and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored that we can be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and have the same members over the years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think that first we are all lucky that we are still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are always interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we respect each other’s music, and I don’t think it could be any better.
Your relationship to the word of glory has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier and easier to find balance.
We try not to ride too much on tour because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people have come for music, you will remember that you have to respect the music and what you have given it. You must not get carried away by being famous, rock stars. This has never really interested any of us.
What do you think of the upcoming Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and in the beginning it was something great.
As a band, we were in existence for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating, because it took so long. The most important thing is that we still be friends today with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy, how I used to like him, how he was so incredulous.
She was an incredible person and we miss her very much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as your forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. That is why we are curious what Las Robertas will offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words "Yellow Ledbetter" live?
That's a question about Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
A lot of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I could talk all night about the bassists that I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt a slight separation from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I think of the bands I’ve mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out at the same time. And if the music is still valid today, then it’s something great because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are better off playing today than ever before.
In the beginning your music had a slightly gloomy character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there’s a few songs in the new album that are easier to digest, but there’s also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, though they may sound positive.
In both of them, when Ed played them to me, I was crying, and the songs are deep dark.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things begin to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent just that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
