Manuel Jon<0xC3><0xA1>s Larraz<0xC3><0xA1>bal has spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after being pardoned by the legal representative of Casino Red before the Second Criminal Court in that district, which was considering a case of extortion in which the brother of the mayor of Monterrey was charged.
After the Casino Royale attack, Casina Red owner Sergio Gil Garc<0xC3><0xAD>a posted a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonas was asked to pay him an economic quota to allow the Monterrey City Hall to operate illegally in a betting house.
After the public prosecution, the State Prosecutor's Office initiated the criminal prosecution of the brother of the panic mayor. On September 2, he was arrested and imprisoned for 30 days.
Then, after 4 hours spent in front of Public Prosecutor's Agent No. 3 for property offenses, he was transferred to Prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo in the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days after a second arrest warrant was issued and a Public Prosecutor's agent denied the possibility of complicity or organized crime.
On 19 October, he was transferred to a criminal court in Cadereyta on suspicion of blackmailing the owners of Casina Red in the amount of one and a half million pesos. However, he remained only a few hours in prison with moderate supervision because he was threatened with death.
During the trial, he was allowed to remain in city cells in San Nicol<0xC3><0xA1>s de los Garza.
On October 25, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the Secretary of the Second Criminal Court, Jorge Y<0xC3><0xA1>nez, who stated that after almost two months of investigation, sufficient evidence had been collected to prove Jonas' guilt. The evidence includes, for example, a payment of 1.5 million euros in fines.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casina Red, V<0xC3><0xAD>ctor Aldo Garc<0xC3><0xAD>a G<0xC3><0xB3>mez, surrendered to the judge José Luis Pecin and asked for mercy for the brother of the mayor of the region. On this basis, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the public prosecutor's representative assigned to this court, Ramiro Arias, asked Garc<0xC3><0xAD>a G<0xC3><0xB3>mez whether the damage had been repaired and which of the partners had decided to grant the pardon.
On the basis of official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jon<0xC3><0xA1>s Larraz<0xC3><0xA1>bal. In the process that was conducted against him, no complaint can be filed. It is also not possible to claim damages or punishment.
After an interview with the legal representative at around 15:50, the court ordered the immediate release of Larraz<0xC3><0xA1>bal Bret<0xC3><0xB3>n.
The court’s secretary, Jorge Yanez, arrived at the prison in San Nicol<0xC3><0xA1>s de los Garza to announce to Jonas that he had been granted an official pardon and that his case had been postponed to the archives.
He also informed him that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come presented details of the plane crash that killed the secretary of the governor, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of an investigation into the crash that killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people showed that the helicopter had hit the ground with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, Secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the launch of the aircraft, the pilot stated that climatic conditions allow flights.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings became entangled in the branches of the trees 25 meters from the place where the unit lost the torso."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, therefore it met all requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he stated that no components were found on the ground as a result of an investigation carried out in the area of the accident.
"In the search, it was found that parts of the plane were not in another location, so the plane came across the land as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all the requirements for transporting people.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment it is most important to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to a year.
Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the crash, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at cruising speed and the accident occurred on soft terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a normal overflight operation," he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come mentioned six basic points of investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the visual flight rules, which means that the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at take-off, in accordance with which the aircraft advances towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility as far as the Cuernavaca Valley.
The location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that before the impact there was no loss of control or disruption of the trajectory of the flight.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information we currently have at our disposal allows us to assume that the collision occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The diagram of the dispersion of the remnants of the aircraft suggests that at the time of the impact on the ground, the helicopter was intact.
There was no fire or explosion.
At the scene of the accident, there was no evidence that there was an explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the land.
During the field work, remnants of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloping, the height of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show images in which there was probably a break-up along the mentioned route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter could have come into contact with the ground at several locations.
After a careful search in the vicinity of the accident, no remains of the helicopter were found in an area larger than the designated area, which reinforces the assumption that the crash occurred in a state where the helicopter was still intact.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has started research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute IPN
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene causing obesity in children and adolescents. Research called "Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents" will allow to obtain results related to overweight.
In a report, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Biochemistry Research Unit at the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research can also be carried out by the general public, with or without permission. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where each council from 8 a.m. will carry out tests for adolescents.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and since October 8 this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Center (Eastern Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He clarified that every Saturday anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) are carried out with all participants, blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes that are involved in the formation of children).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said this research reflects health care providers’ concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys had an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight,' said an expert from the IMSS.
He said that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country is different from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of the Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% of the European and 5% of the African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the formation of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they are given an overall assessment of the condition of the children, which will determine whether they are overweight or obese.
He said that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential so far, doctors hand it over in writing to the parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid their children getting sick.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day and using means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Excess weight is also caused by a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic load that is the subject of this research.
Asphalt from UNAM will not be emptied
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the landfill was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 landfills after each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, said Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of the landfills were to be completed, it would be possible to repair the landfill.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Extinction, which he gave in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, thus creating a mixture having similar characteristics to asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, as well as to it.
Herrer N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of landslides.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight, which are called asphaltenes, and others with a low molecular weight, which are called maltenes. Together they supply asphalt typical viscous.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, noted the expert on chemical engineering.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with a flexible tile consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the highest layers is the asphalt insert, formed by small stones poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that forms an insert is poured with asphalt.
When passing cars or when creating pressure, it is possible for forces in the tile to decompose well.
If it were a modified asphalt, it would have decomposed even better, according to a chemical engineer.
He added that on the asphalt insert is placed the last layer called the mantle, formed by fine stones, that is, sand also poured into the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of the vehicles, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
Since as part of the paving will be exposed to a large load, the shell must be of sufficient thickness and attention must be paid to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inward and it is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the tile and thus the formation of mulch.
He explained that during the formation of abrasions, the film of the casing is first destroyed and then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one moment, but it is a slow process that should be stopped at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of debris, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of the pavement must correspond to the load of vehicles and must guarantee that this load will not be exceeded.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that we still have a lot of work ahead of us when it comes to asphalt and research is at the beginning. For example, asphalt emulsions are worth mentioning, which are already available in other countries on the market and make it easy to repair excavations without having to use high temperatures.
