This was the work of Cali, who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cana.
An expert on fingerprints from Cali went down in history as a man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cana.
The work of these officials is crucial.
On 4 November last year, a fingerprint expert from the CTI in Cali made history as a man who confirmed the identity of Farc's supreme leader: "Alfonse Cana", through a comparison of fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprinting experts working in the CTI department, Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, a man from Puerta Tejada who has been working in forensic research for 21 years, was in line this week.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked at the town hall in Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where he often had to spend more than five days exploring the forest to get to the place where the bodies had to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital of Valle and after taking the appropriate courses, he began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of the friction of the skin, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to take his clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night he went to Cauc in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he would have to identify two bodies and that he suspected one of them was a man who was leading the world's oldest guerrilla. That's why they asked him to take a card with fingerprints of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n Saenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigating team at the place where the body was located, he did not recognize it because of the physical appearance. He looked completely different than in the media.
He had no beard, dressed like a villager in a given area, without glasses, much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with a galton magnifying glass, ink, and a transplanter, Eliazar began to compare the dactylic records of the corpse with those of the card.
Her eye did not disappoint: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, a man from Puerto Tejada was commissioned to confirm to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n, whether he was indeed the supreme commander of the Farc.
Searching for Stops
For the dactyloscope from Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n de Cali, the recognition given to Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez by President Juan Manuel Santos at the press conference of the operational service against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no possibility of error, which can play a key role in the decision-making of crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, these people help investigate crimes such as theft or murder and confirm the identity of the persons caught.
When caught, a lot of delinquents present false documents or have no papers at all.
We'll take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator told that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the wall of the house in the house, because in this place the thief leaned to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not intended for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to get a full handprint and identify the perpetrator who participated in several thefts,” he said.
Fingerprints can also confirm or disprove suspicions in the event of a murder.
They recently found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
Based on the investigation, it turned out that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder, and the imprint on the bottle actually confirmed this.
Although it cannot be 100% confirmed that he was indeed a murderer, it is clear that he appeared on the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint expert explained that the fingerprints “are erased using chemical or physical reactive substances” from the objects.
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to collect them.
Then the prints are sent to Asif, which is a database of criminals, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians whose data is not recorded anywhere at the moment," the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the TV program CSI.
Just as everything that glitters is not gold, not everything that you touch remains traces.
