'Indignation' Protests in New York City
Hundreds of protesters crowded into Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to live.
A large part of them were waiting for the order to clear the space and moved to a nearby park.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement provoked New York officials on Tuesday when they tried to get back to Manhattan Square with a court order, from where they were taken out in the morning, then tried to take over another New York park.
Hundreds of protesters rushed to Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to get to thanks to a court order that allows the "angry" to return to settle on the spot. The second part of the movement responded to the eviction by taking the park to the north of the city, where further detentions took place.
"If the court does not allow us to return to the square, we will settle in another place and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, both through assembly and peaceful demonstrations," said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Wall Street Movement.
Bray clarified that the response of the “angry” to the camp’s displacement, ordered by New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg himself, reached the court, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the violent displacement of the site and allowing the protesters to establish themselves here and there.
In addition, the "anger" took over another park located at the intersection of Central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, near the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and the land of the lighthouse in Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to take the place, but then the police came and detained some protesters. Bray did not know the exact number, but said that he saw that some journalists had also been chained.
The organization assures that several hundred people have settled on the site. Also, a delegation of religious representatives came to express their support and also tried to negotiate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square, which is a private property, remains closed. A court hearing is expected, which should take place on Tuesday, and during which the legality of the morning evacuation should be analyzed.
Some of the displaced protesters even distributed and handed out copies of the court order and even gave them to members who were guarding the square, which caused "some small clashes", Bray said, condemning the fact that some police protesters were beaten.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting members of the Ocupa Wall Street movement or applying “laws that were published after the lockdown began, or prohibiting protesters from accessing the park with shops or other places they used to use.”
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that due to this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of public space and the protesters warned that local laws would not allow them to return to their tents and dormitories.
The city’s top official personally defended the early evacuation of Zuccotti Square, an operation that detained 200 people and was acceded to because protesters “violated the law.”
Bloomberg explained that he had ordered the evacuation of the square because it had become “a place where people did not go to protest but to break the laws and in some cases hurt others” because “some shops received threatening letters” and “neighbors were concerned about the quality of their lives”.
“The early clean-up was appalling and shows that Bloomberg is trying to maintain financial interests at the expense of the American working people,” said a spokesman for the movement, which accused the mayor of “not respecting freedom of expression.”
Representatives of the Occupy Wall Street movement also said they plan to hold "big events" on Thursday in cooperation with community and trade union organizations to remind them of the two months of protests, which began on September 17.
