Initial estimates by the Tokyo government have put the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that is healing well despite the difficult global situation.
After three quarters of declines, the value of GDP between July and September reached such a position that it was possible to turn the page with definitive validity: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% per year.
In addition, the results of the second quarter - for the Japanese, the tax year begins in March 2012 - assume the highest growth rate compared to the period January to March 2010.
The revival can be partly explained by the purchase of machines that are necessary for the restoration of areas destroyed by earthquakes and subsequent tsunamis.
Companies increased their investments by 1.1%, spending fell by 0.9% compared to the period January to March. This is the first decline after six months of continuous growth.
However, the real awakening of the Japanese economy is based solely on the impulse that forces us to use the crisis to get out of it, or to rebuild infrastructure, and that is to use the shortfall to start from scratch.
Japan has woken up, thanks in particular to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, thanks to an increase in spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
Stigma yenu
