This is one of the conclusions of the extensive report of the Royal Canadian Society, which was attended by six experts working in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The commission recommends that the government amend the criminal law to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia if this choice appears necessary for a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the beginning, experts cite a recent survey by the independent agency Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the planet.
Although Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has given rise to a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death.”
Medicalization yes or no, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts with the mandate of the Royal Canadian Society tell us.
And despite the desire to die at home that most Canadians have, 68.6% of them die in hospital.
This average applies to all of Canada, while in the province of Quebec, this figure is highest with 86% of hospital deaths.
With regard to the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything about the criminal law regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
According to experts who have also checked all countries where these approaches are legalized or not considered a criminal case, there is no evidence that this decriminalization causes any abuse in the application, i.e. in the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide of persons who are incompetent or disapproving.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, confirmed more than a number of cases of such concussions in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalised.
"Euthanasia is also carried out in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
“Assisted suicide is also being carried out in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians are in favour of euthanasia.
According to a 2010 survey conducted by the Angus Reid Forum, 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia because they believe it will allow people at the end of their lives to ease their suffering.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not mean we are sending a message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are of lesser value.
In terms of people practising assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing patient care, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
They also suggest in the list of their recommendations that criminal law states that withdrawal from treatment, for which there is a legally confirmed refusal, is not a criminal offence.
The Commission also requires professional doctors to be trained to respect the end-of-life refusal of treatment without fear of prosecution.
With regard to palliative care, the Commission urgently requires governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, including in cancer cases.
Finally, in the case of palliative or final silence already widely used in Canadian medical facilities, the Commission requires that it be considered as euthanasia when it no longer serves to reduce physical pain and to be subject to the same procedures.
