Some medical law experts have already expressed their reservations about the findings of the Royal Canadian Society’s expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in medical law, qualified the position of expert-signatories of the report as "extreme" among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to patients in the final stage.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide," said Pierre Deschamps, who studied the report's summary yesterday.
P. Deschamps also stresses that it seems that the authors of the report build the autonomy of the person above all other values that form the social fabric of society.
For "in society, he says, there are warning signs and restrictions".
Medical law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong objections to the conclusions of the report, which she qualified as a "manifesto for euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Canadian Society, particularly doubts the dates of the report on the absence of error in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, i.e. in the Netherlands and in the US state of Oregon.
