Writing the Golden Rule on a Balanced Budget into the Constitution
The government of a large coalition of social democrats and Christian democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to sign the "golden rule" of budget policy into the constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid any reduction in Austria's rating by rating agencies (AA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the conclusion of the Council of Ministers in a situation where, with its 74.6% public debt, it is high above the criterion of a maximum of 60% set by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy.
“If Austria’s solvency were to be reduced by just one degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more each year on interest,” argued Michael Spindelegger, a Christian Democrat.
Austria is thus following up on the request of the Eurozone Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the Heads of State and Government strongly requested that by the end of 2012 the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of the balance of public accounts be enshrined in the Constitution or in the Values Act.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is approaching the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year, and starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while federal countries, as well as municipalities, will have to report a balance sheet.
The aim is to bring public debt below the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
