Energy Policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balances or under emotions, then it is energy policy.
The availability and price of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is natural that an election meeting should be an opportunity to think about such deposits and about a place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will be successful only if all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
So far, there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic developments will double the demand for electricity by 2050 if we do not want to deprive a significant part of the world’s population of important parts of life.
At the same time, it will be necessary to face a shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity, while not forgetting the necessary need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, which is a topic that is currently disappearing from environmentalists.
The accident in Fukushima does not affect any of these parameters.
And that is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear energy.
However, this is not the case for Belgium, which is subject to its decision to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which considers it appropriate to build only the latest generation of power plants.
On the contrary, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, continue with determination in their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by rebuilding a single power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island power plant disaster.
If a German model based on renewable energies is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts it.
The choice of Berlin will be manifested by the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on gas imported especially from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal-fired power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves to be considered.
The European champion in wind power plants, of which it receives 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to the irregularity of the wind, due to which CO2 emissions and Danish electricity prices are higher by 65% and 50%, respectively, than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay 40% more electricity bills than the French households pay.
While in a globalised economy, energy costs are a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industry on national territory, French companies enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
The price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, as well as do not fundamentally oppose this energy, as public opinion polls show.
Recall that our country’s energy policy has allowed to build an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 consecutive jobs.
The highly-exporting sector is attracting large numbers of small and medium-sized specialised jobs to international markets that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France decided to leave the core, it would sacrifice a small number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and lose the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion a year that the country receives for the export of nuclear facilities and services.
Which power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to run for 60 years while its manufacturer is scheduled to fail?
In solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magic source for energy production, nor is there any diabolical one.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable energy facilities by the French industrial group AREVA is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is absolutely necessary to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the State Nuclear Safety Authority, which conducts uncompromising and transparent oversight of existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of a new plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in the blood.
In fifty years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major accidents.
The only one on Three Mile Island appeared under normal operating conditions and was left without human casualties and environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the drama caused the concept of the reactor and inexcusable human error.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented scale that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will take lessons from this accident just as it did from the two previous ones.
The result of this step and the cooperation between the French and German authorities dealing with nuclear safety, operators and constructors is that the EPR reactor represents a concept capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all those interested in building a nuclear power plant consider it, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift offered to AREVA’s and EDF’s competitors and paving the way for them to seize leadership positions in nuclear development.
