Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles – the squandering of police, courts and administrations subjected to the policy of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of “land of human rights”, which France boasts.
Recently, this was an administrative nuisance, the object of which was foreign students, which became topical when the Minister of the Interior (see the May 23 issue of Libération) declared that France “does not need foreign talents, masons and waitresses”.
But so far, it has rarely been analyzed from an economic perspective.
It must be said that there is a fairly broad agreement between the left and the right in this area.
To the right, Jacques Chirac declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem in a country with 2 million migrant workers" and on the left, Michel Rocard, when he said in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of a horde of Polish installers invading French territory was shared right and left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference lies in the degree of generosity that we are giving to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande limits himself to banality when he states that joint development will allow us to solve our “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden and problem may apply in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As the economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in their recently published work, “Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future,” a broad consensus on migration exists among specialists, as well as a broad consensus on migration.
Restricting immigration is stunting growth and harming employment.
Concerns about the impact caused by migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less qualified, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are much more complements than substitutes for French employees by doing work in sectors with a shortage of employees.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and those most qualified in dynamic sectors where education is not enough to offer jobs.
Positive impact on wages
Just as a surgeon will have trouble working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthesiologists, these additions between the French and migrants cause the arrivals of immigrants to have a positive impact on the salaries and employment of French employees.
Giovanni Peri calculated that the growth of migration movements by 1% will lead to a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And it does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries, averaging 1% of the total budget.
The World Labor Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany one immigrant coming at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (receipts minus expenses) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to public budgets for his entire life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy expressed his desire to make up for the lack of growth percentages "with precious teeth".
The aforementioned teeth used to deter immigrants had the opposite effect.
