Nord Stream, the new port of entry for Russian gas into Europe
The long-distance Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to operate.
It must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday’s inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have jointly turned the control valve of the Russian gas inlet into the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe every year, the first pipeline of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region with the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline, to be completed at the end of 2012, will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to the total French consumption.
And it already reminds us of the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge construction is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being routed through the country by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some of their power: the possibility of pressuring Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream with the "new German-Soviet pact", with the reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that this is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained greater certainty in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project has created rifts between Europeans from the east and west.
Just five years ago, Russia succeeded in advancing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western states with high gas consumption, whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically," Fillon said at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large-scale gas contracts are a matter of both political and economic importance.
All this explains the wide smiles of the leaders of Gazprom present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas inlet.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical feat.
The undersea pipeline is made of steel fitted with a concrete shell to protect it from the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the time of World War II.
“For safety reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing like 242 Eiffel Towers, which throughout its length is not interrupted by either valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were only reluctant to see the Russian state-owned company permanently settling off their shores.
"In the event of a fault, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute," says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders, because the welds were designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
Control of the condition of the pipeline from the outside is carried out by a submarine robot drawn by the ship, while the interior of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the interior of the pipe and is pressurized with gas.
At the destination after three days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline has been designed to work for fifty years without the slightest need for repair.
Circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake, remains in the lead.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in the city of Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company for five years under a contract, which can be renewed, all its gas transmission capacities.
"Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported," M<0xC3><0xBC>ller said.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of labor should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves with a height of 4.5 meters form an outlet for gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When reaching full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 6 million.
