Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today is the 15th week for the employment of disabled people.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% versus 9% for the entire population.
Is it depressing?
"No, underlines <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Disability Employment Week."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher."
"Nevertheless, much remains to be done."
It has to be said that for unemployed disabled people, there are still numerous obstacles to their entry into employment.
These are older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low qualification: 80% do not have a degree and out of 2.3 million university students there are only 10,000 people with disabilities.
And finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, such are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work and which constitute the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of the Tremplin Association, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
So much for objective braking.
It remains unspoken, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about people with disabilities" with "an exaggerated idea of people in a wheelchair and mental or mental disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the target of employing 6% of disabled workers set out in the 1987 law.
The last known figures, which come from 2008, indicate a level of 2.6%.
“We are now moving around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, which is responsible for collecting fees from businesses that do not comply with the law.
The proof is the number of "punished" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which decreased between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 guilty enterprises to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
